00:03:08.919 --> 00:03:12.199
So if you have a data in a SQL server

00:03:12.199 --> 00:03:15.720
and you can push certain operations to that SQL server

00:03:15.720 --> 00:03:18.119
so that it transforms your data, cleans it up,

00:03:18.119 --> 00:03:19.880
you pull in the data that you want,

00:03:19.880 --> 00:03:21.639
then that's a great solution for your team.

00:03:21.679 --> 00:03:24.440
I think APIs in the context we presented it today

00:03:24.440 --> 00:03:28.000
as kind of like a data portal, so to speak,

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:29.559
you can do a lot of those same things.

00:03:29.559 --> 00:03:32.279
So it's really gonna depend on how your team operates.

00:03:32.279 --> 00:03:35.960
If Microsoft SQL works well for you, then that's awesome.

00:03:35.960 --> 00:03:37.399
We certainly wouldn't say,

00:03:37.399 --> 00:03:40.240
jump ship from that and switch over to an API,

00:03:40.240 --> 00:03:42.559
but just know that an API is a data access portal

00:03:42.559 --> 00:03:44.279
is a great solution as well.

