00:08:20.119 --> 00:08:21.959
It was, are there any examples yet

00:08:21.959 --> 00:08:26.200
of people publishing datasets in various data repositories

00:08:26.200 --> 00:08:30.519
for further query and analysis of published datasets?

00:08:31.519 --> 00:08:34.840
Are there any examples yet of people publishing datasets

00:08:34.840 --> 00:08:37.280
in various data repositories?

00:08:37.280 --> 00:08:39.000
Katie or Ralph, any ideas?

00:08:42.200 --> 00:08:44.799
Off the top of my head, I'm not aware of any,

00:08:44.799 --> 00:08:48.320
but I'm certain there probably are some.

00:08:48.320 --> 00:08:52.760
Yeah, I mean, there are various open data initiatives,

00:08:52.760 --> 00:08:57.760
of course, but so far I haven't seen anything standardized.

00:08:57.760 --> 00:09:02.760
But quite often then there are packages or Python packages

00:09:03.080 --> 00:09:04.520
that you can use to access

00:09:04.520 --> 00:09:08.919
these non-standard data repositories.

00:09:10.520 --> 00:09:13.880
And if anyone has ideas or links,

00:09:13.880 --> 00:09:16.039
feel free to share those in the chat too.

00:09:19.719 --> 00:09:24.719
Okay, so another question I see from YouTube was,

00:09:25.679 --> 00:09:27.799
could you discuss the pros and cons

00:09:27.799 --> 00:09:30.919
of Pins versus FastAPI for Shiny?

00:09:33.280 --> 00:09:35.039
Yeah, that's a good question.

00:09:35.039 --> 00:09:39.000
And thankfully I'm joined by one of our Pins experts,

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:42.479
Katie, but I can at least talk a little bit about it

00:09:42.479 --> 00:09:44.520
and then pass the mic over.

00:09:44.520 --> 00:09:47.440
But Pins, and if you actually go back

00:09:47.440 --> 00:09:50.119
to our last month's demo, I believe,

00:09:50.119 --> 00:09:52.440
we actually talked a little bit more about Pins

00:09:52.440 --> 00:09:53.799
and how you can use it.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:56.880
And we did it in the context of just grabbing a data set

00:09:56.880 --> 00:09:58.960
and pulling it into a Corridor document

00:09:58.960 --> 00:10:00.960
or a Shiny application, for example.

00:10:02.280 --> 00:10:06.280
But Pins, for the most part, they're fairly static.

00:10:06.280 --> 00:10:07.520
So you have a data set,

00:10:07.520 --> 00:10:10.000
you clean it up using our Markdown or Corridor,

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:11.840
and then you pin it, same way you would pin

00:10:11.840 --> 00:10:14.320
or save something to like Dropbox

00:10:14.320 --> 00:10:16.599
or Google Drive or something like that.

00:10:16.599 --> 00:10:18.080
And once it's there, you can share it,

00:10:18.080 --> 00:10:20.200
and that's a great use case.

00:10:20.200 --> 00:10:22.479
But a benefit for like FastAPI

00:10:22.520 --> 00:10:26.159
is that not only can it serve as like a data portal

00:10:26.159 --> 00:10:27.000
for you to get data,

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:29.440
but you can also do things to that data.

00:10:29.440 --> 00:10:30.799
And so from our webinar today,

00:10:30.799 --> 00:10:33.000
you saw that I pinged the API,

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:35.520
but at the same time, I added some query items.

00:10:35.520 --> 00:10:38.679
So I said to API, like, hey, I want the data,

00:10:38.679 --> 00:10:40.640
but only give me the data where the rows

00:10:40.640 --> 00:10:42.599
are equal to like A, B, and C.

00:10:42.599 --> 00:10:45.799
And then I get that data back, so only that data.

00:10:45.799 --> 00:10:48.359
So there are ways FastAPI can probably

00:10:48.359 --> 00:10:50.799
do a little bit more compute for you.

00:10:50.799 --> 00:10:53.919
You can place it into a function in Python and R

00:10:53.919 --> 00:10:56.679
and kind of wrap those functions into an API.

00:10:56.679 --> 00:11:00.159
A lot of the work you would do in your Shiny application,

00:11:00.159 --> 00:11:02.679
you can essentially push to an API.

00:11:02.679 --> 00:11:04.880
And that's always a lot of times best practice

00:11:04.880 --> 00:11:06.119
when I'm speaking with folks

00:11:06.119 --> 00:11:08.159
that have these Shiny applications,

00:11:08.159 --> 00:11:12.359
and they're big, they're clunky, they're slow.

00:11:12.359 --> 00:11:14.880
I say, you know, if you can take any compute,

00:11:14.880 --> 00:11:17.239
anything that doesn't need to be in that Shiny application

00:11:17.239 --> 00:11:19.799
and move it to something like an API

00:11:19.799 --> 00:11:22.799
or maybe a core to a document scheduled to run or a pin,

00:11:22.799 --> 00:11:26.000
just kind of move that stuff outside of the Shiny app,

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:29.520
that typically will set you up for success in the future.

00:11:29.520 --> 00:11:32.159
But Katie, Ralph, anything to add?

00:11:34.799 --> 00:11:37.520
Yeah, I think that's pretty solid, Ryan.

00:11:37.520 --> 00:11:42.520
The big difference that I think of is an API,

00:11:42.559 --> 00:11:44.719
whether it's FastAPI, Plumber, right?

00:11:44.719 --> 00:11:48.239
It's just a way of wrapping up a function.

00:11:48.239 --> 00:11:49.960
So you're doing something.

00:11:49.960 --> 00:11:52.840
And in the demo that you did today, right?

00:11:52.840 --> 00:11:57.520
Your function was accessing a data frame and filtering it.

00:11:57.520 --> 00:12:00.559
But it could be a function that creates a model

00:12:00.559 --> 00:12:04.679
or does a coin toss or whatever it is.

00:12:04.679 --> 00:12:06.679
And so it's doing a function

00:12:06.679 --> 00:12:09.080
and that's just wrapped up as an API.

00:12:09.080 --> 00:12:12.799
Whereas a pin is you pin an object,

00:12:12.799 --> 00:12:16.880
whether it's a data frame, an image, a list or whatever,

00:12:16.880 --> 00:12:19.599
it's an object that's put into a place

00:12:19.599 --> 00:12:21.960
where you can share or collaborate

00:12:21.960 --> 00:12:25.479
or reuse in different places.

00:12:25.479 --> 00:12:28.280
So it's sort of different use cases.

00:12:28.280 --> 00:12:30.520
We sort of saw a bit of an intersection today

00:12:30.520 --> 00:12:33.039
for the use of sharing data,

00:12:33.039 --> 00:12:35.559
but under the hood, just keep in mind that APIs,

00:12:35.559 --> 00:12:38.840
you're going to be a bundling up of a function

00:12:38.840 --> 00:12:39.679
under the hood.

00:12:41.559 --> 00:12:42.440
Thanks, Katie.

00:12:43.599 --> 00:12:46.640
I see John asked a question over on YouTube

00:12:47.400 --> 00:12:49.080
that said, am I right in thinking this approach

00:12:49.080 --> 00:12:50.640
will make it fairly straightforward

00:12:50.640 --> 00:12:53.000
to link up-to-date summary info

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:55.520
with something like a React app?

00:12:55.520 --> 00:12:58.320
This really helps keep the front-end language agnostic.

00:13:01.280 --> 00:13:02.479
Yeah, I would think so.

00:13:04.400 --> 00:13:09.039
That's exactly one of the nice use cases for APIs

00:13:09.039 --> 00:13:11.320
to have potentially multiple front-ends

00:13:11.320 --> 00:13:12.919
for one piece of logic.

00:13:13.320 --> 00:13:14.559
Mm-hmm.

00:13:14.559 --> 00:13:16.919
Yeah, when I was working on this content,

00:13:16.919 --> 00:13:18.960
I was speaking with some folks at Positive,

00:13:18.960 --> 00:13:21.479
like, you know, what's really the big thing

00:13:21.479 --> 00:13:23.599
that advantage APIs provides?

00:13:23.599 --> 00:13:25.440
And it's exactly what Ralph mentioned.

00:13:25.440 --> 00:13:28.799
You might have completely different pieces of content.

00:13:28.799 --> 00:13:31.320
So we talked about Shiny app in R,

00:13:31.320 --> 00:13:33.599
Jupyter Notebook in Python or React app.

00:13:33.599 --> 00:13:36.440
It could be something completely different,

00:13:36.440 --> 00:13:40.159
but APIs provide that kind of common communication layer

00:13:40.159 --> 00:13:41.719
so that it can speak to those functions

00:13:41.719 --> 00:13:44.440
that you developed in Python in R or whatever.

00:13:44.440 --> 00:13:45.520
So again, I always like to go back

00:13:45.520 --> 00:13:46.799
to that restaurant analogy.

00:13:46.799 --> 00:13:49.760
So your API is the waiter or waitress

00:13:49.760 --> 00:13:52.119
that allows the customers to speak to the chef.

00:13:52.119 --> 00:13:54.840
Customers might be from different parts of the world,

00:13:54.840 --> 00:13:56.000
speak different languages,

