00:16:10.559 --> 00:16:15.000
how would you choose which API framework to use?

00:16:16.880 --> 00:16:17.719
Yeah.

00:16:18.919 --> 00:16:22.239
So I'm an R developer,

00:16:22.239 --> 00:16:24.039
more so than I am a Python developer,

00:16:24.039 --> 00:16:25.239
but you'll notice today.

00:16:26.880 --> 00:16:30.080
If I had to very quickly on the fly create an API,

00:16:30.080 --> 00:16:33.239
I would certainly probably try to use Plumber

00:16:33.239 --> 00:16:35.119
because that is kind of a wrapper

00:16:35.119 --> 00:16:36.799
on the R programming language.

00:16:36.799 --> 00:16:38.520
I'm just a little bit more comfortable with that.

00:16:38.520 --> 00:16:40.159
But if you're a Python developer,

00:16:40.159 --> 00:16:42.640
you may be more comfortable with FastAPI.

00:16:42.640 --> 00:16:44.479
So I think the take-home here is that

00:16:44.479 --> 00:16:47.239
whatever you're most comfortable leveraging,

00:16:47.239 --> 00:16:49.359
you can find a framework for creating APIs.

00:16:49.359 --> 00:16:54.359
So Plumber for R, FastAPI, Flask in the Python ecosystem.

00:16:55.679 --> 00:16:59.039
And again, you don't have to be a computer scientist

00:16:59.039 --> 00:17:01.679
or a software engineer to create these APIs.

00:17:01.679 --> 00:17:03.239
You really just need to know a little bit of R

00:17:03.239 --> 00:17:05.760
or a little bit of Python to create these APIs.

00:17:08.199 --> 00:17:09.040
